         <abstract>
            <p>The Maṣḥafa Taklil (lit. ‘Book of the Crowning’) is the ritual of matrimony of the Ethiopian Orthodox Tawāḥǝdo Church. Its title
               is due to the fact that bride and groom wear crowns during the wedding ceremony. 
               <bibl><ptr target="bm:Guidi1932storia"/><citedRange unit="page">75</citedRange></bibl> dated its composition to the 
               seventeenth century. The Maṣḥafa Taklil consists of three parts, corresponding to the three parts of the rite. The first part, for the
               Service of Betrothal (<foreign xml:lang="gez">ḥǝḍʿāt</foreign>, the rite is also known as 
               <foreign xml:lang="gez">Śǝrʿāta fǝḫrat</foreign> lit. ‘Rite of Betrothal’), is composed of six ‘commandments’ 
               (<foreign xml:lang="gez">tǝʾǝzāzāt</foreign>). In this part, the bride and the bridegroom confirm their voluntary agreement to
               marry in front of the priest and the public and exchange testament rings. The second part, the Service of Matrimony 
               (<foreign xml:lang="gez">kabkāb</foreign>), contains the reading for the rite celebrated on Sunday after the matins. The third 
               part is the actual rite of the Holy Matrimony (<foreign xml:lang="gez">Śǝrʿāta mǝśṭira taklil</foreign>, lit. ‘Rite of the Mystery
               [i.e. ‘Sacrament’] of Crowning’).</p>
         </abstract>
